Reference-contexts: 1 Introduction A sparse distributed memory (SDM) is a model of human long-term memory developed by Kanerva that may offer a new approach to problems in machine learning <ref> [Kanerva, 1988] </ref>. The memory supports approximate addressing, which means that an item stored in the memory can be retrieved by addressing the memory with an address sufficiently similar, but not necessarily identical, to the original address with which the item was written. <p> A k-fold memory allows prediction of successive patterns based on the previous k patterns of the sequence. For a more detailed description of the sparse distributed memory model, the reader is referred to <ref> [Kanerva, 1988] </ref>.
